blockStates.name: A Nano Gear
blockStates.userText:
Macroscopic machines often use rotating shafts and gears to drive motion. Molecular machines can do similar things using parts in ways that follow conventional engineering practice.

A differential gear links two shafts through a casing, constraining the sum of the rotational angles of the shafts to equal the rotational angle of the casing. In a car, a differential gear lets the engine drive the wheels while letting them roll different distances in cornering. A molecular differential gear like that shown in this page, designed by K. Eric Drexler, can serve this vital automotive function, but in a volume a few nanometers on a side, containing only 8,297 atoms.
